data.name: label2.Text
data.value: This sample application shows you how to configure a compressed shard. A compressed shard is mostly used by SaaS application vendors that want to isolate a customer database from other databases. This library makes it easy to isolate T-SQL query execution for individual customers while controlling each customer's database in a configuration database. This library also allows you to use SQL Database (in Azure) or SQL Server, or a combination of both as needed. Last but not least, this library allows you to easily setup an environment in which each customers' tables/objects are stored in different schemas on one or more databases.

data.name: label8.Text
data.value: The sharding library expects a root database with configuration tables that provide the details of the configuration. The script to create the root database is located in this project (CreateRootDB.SQL). Below are two sample configurations that this library supports: one customer per DB, and multiple customers by DB. Figure 2 shows you that you can have a mixed model, where some customers reside on the same database, while others have a dedicated database (for performance or security reasons). Each server below (SRV1 or SRV2) can be the same server, on different machines, or a mix of SQL Database and SQL Server.
